{"id":"0809.1178","submitter":"Changkun Xie","authors":"C. K. Xie, J. I. Budnick, W. A. Hines, B. O. Wells, and J. C. Woicik","title":"Local Structure and It's Effect on The Ferromagnetic Properties of\n  La$_{0.5}$Sr$_{0.5}$CoO$_3$ thin films}","comments":"4 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/1.3011031","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We have used high-resolution Extended X-ray Absorption Fine-Structure and\ndiffraction techniques to measure the local structure of strained\nLa$_{0.5}$Sr$_{0.5}$CoO$_3$ films under compression and tension. The lattice\nmismatch strain in these compounds affects both the bond lengths and the bond\nangles, though the larger effect on the bandwidth is due to the bond length\nchanges. The popular double exchange model for ferromagnetism in these\ncompounds provides a correct qualitative description of the changes in Curie\ntemperature $T_C$, but quantitatively underestimates the changes. A microscopic\nmodel for ferromagnetism that provides a much stronger dependence on the\nstructural distortions is needed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 6 Sep 2008 15:19:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 4 Nov 2008 15:37:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-13"}
{"id":"0809.1180","submitter":"Patricia Faisca","authors":"P.F.N. Faisca and C. M. Gomes","title":"On the relation between native geometry and conformational plasticity","comments":"Accepted in Biophysical Chemistry","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"q-bio.BM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In protein folding the term plasticity refers to the number of alternative\nfolding pathways encountered in response to free energy perturbations such as\nthose induced by mutation. Here we explore the relation between folding\nplasticity and a gross, generic feature of the native geometry, namely, the\nrelative number of local and non-local native contacts. The results from our\nstudy, which is based on Monte Carlo simulations of simple lattice proteins,\nshow that folding to a structure that is rich in local contacts is considerably\nmore plastic than folding to a native geometry characterized by having a very\nlarge number of long-range contacts (i.e., contacts between amino acids that\nare separated by more than 12 units of backbone distance). The smaller folding\nplasticity of `non-local' native geometries is probably a direct consequence of\ntheir higher folding cooperativity that renders the folding reaction more\nrobust against single- and multiple-point mutations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 6 Sep 2008 15:45:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-09-09"}
